er altogether except for use in firearms.  If I was a terrorist I'd just buy small amounts of powder over the course of a long time until I had all I needed for whatever diabolical scheme was at hand.  I doubt if most serious terrorists would limit themselves to sources in the USA for the powder in the first place.  As with gun control laws, the only people who will likely be affected by this legislation are the innocent and the law abiding.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/1/03 1:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  news from the Senate</span><hr size=1> Here is the text coming out of Sen. Enzi's office. You are welcome to pass this information on to members of the media.<br>
<br>
Sen. Enzi is drafting legislation that would exempt hobbyists from some of the requirements under the Homeland Security Act, but his work is still in the preliminary stages. I don't have any details and along that same line, Sen. Enzi is also considering the best strategy for introducing/passing the legislation. That means timing. He has not decided on a timeline yet. He is well aware that some problems, e.g. shipping, associated with the Homeland Security bill are already cropping up even though the new rules are not scheduled to take effect until May 24.<br>
<br>
Sen. Enzi is working to build up support from his colleagues on both sides of the aisle for an effort to fix the update to the Safe Explosives Act of 1970 that was included in the Homeland Security bill.<br>
<br>
He has not received a response from the ATF.<br>
<br>
As soon as there are new developments that I can report I will let you know.<br>
<br>
Below is the text of two letters Sen. Enzi has sent on this subject that I think explain the problem and where Sen. Enzi stands on the issue. I hope you find it helpful.<br>
<br>
Thanks for your interest,<br>
Coy<br>
<br>
<br>
Coy Knobel<br>
Press Secretary<br>
U.S. Sen. Mike Enzi<br>
<br>
-----------------<br>
<br>
January 27, 2003<br>
<br>
<br>
Honorable Joseph I. Lieberman<br>
Ranking Member<br>
Committee on Governmental Affairs<br>
United States Senate<br>
340 Dirksen Office Building<br>
Washington, DC 20510<br>
<br>
Dear Joseph:<br>
<br>
I am writing to express my concern about the inclusion of specific provisions within the Homeland Security Act that will adversely affect hobby and consumer rocketry.<br>
<br>
Some provisions included in the Homeland Security Act place severe restrictions on hobby and consumer rocketry, which I do not believe was Congress' intent when drafting and passing this important legislation. Under the new law, the hobbyist will have to obtain Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) permits to purchase a consumer rocket motor and to transport it to the location where it will be flown. Even the simplest permit under the law will require the hobbyist to be subjected to a background check by the ATF. The law also requires all permit holders to keep records that can be inspected by ATF agents. Since these records are primarily kept in the permit holder's home, it subjects the hobbyist's home to possible ATF visits. The response by Americans to these new restrictions will disengage them from the hobby of rocketry, possibly destroying many small businesses and educational hands-on rocketry programs.<br>
<br>
In addition to the new homeland security restrictions, I am told the ATF has misinterpreted what constitutes an explosive. Congress defined an explosive as any chemical mixture or device whose primary or common purpose is to function by explosion. The ATF claims that the primary or common purpose of a rocket propellant (i.e. ammonium perchlorate composite propellant) is to explode. I am told that if the ATF's interpretation is true, a hobbyist's rocket motor would explode upon ignition. A rocket propellant is not designed or intended to explode.<br>
<br>
Enclosed is a letter I recently sent to the ATF inquiring about its interpretation of what constitutes an explosive and requesting they change the classification of a rocket propellant from an explosive to a nonexplosive. However, I believe the Congress should act immediately to make this techical correction to the Homeland Security Act so rocketry is exempt from the Safe Explosives Act.<br>
<br>
Thank you for immediate assistance with my request. Please do not hesitate to contact me or my staff at 224-3424 to further discuss this issue.<br>
<br>
Sincerely,<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Michael B. Enzi<br>
United States Senator<br>
<br>
--------------<br>
<br>
January 27, 2003<br>
<br>
<br>
Honorable Bradley Buckles<br>
Director<br>
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives<br>
United States Department of Justice<br>
650 Massachusetts Avenue, NW<br>
Washington, DC 20226<br>
<br>
Dear Mr. Buckles:<br>
<br>
I am writing to request the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives (ATF) to change its classification of a rocket propellant from an explosive to a nonexplosive.<br>
<br>
As you know, the Congress included provisions in the Homeland Security Act placing severe restrictions on hobby and consumer rocketry. Congress defined an explosive as any chemical mixture or device whose primary or common purpose is to function by explosion. I am told the ATF claims that the primary or common purpose of a rocket propellant (i.e. ammonium perchlorate composite propellant) is to explode. A rocket propellant is not designed or intended to explode. Due to this classification confusion and new homeland security restrictions, many small businesses and educational hands-on rocketry programs will be adversely affected and possibly shut down.<br>
<br>
Please send me any information you deem necessary for me to review in relation to the ATF's classification of rocket propellant.<br>
<br>
Thank you for your immediate assistance in this important matter.<br>
Sincerely,<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Michael B. Enzi<br>
United States Senator  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/1/03 1:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  some background on the issue</span><hr size=1> Hobby rocketry has an unprecendented record of safety.  Launches are managed by experienced people, every rocket  gets a safety inspection, all flyers must be certified by a recognized national rocketry organization to purchase High Power rocket motors, and at their launches, only flyers who have successfully passed a certification process can fly motors according to their level of certification.<br>
<br>
The Alcohol, Tobaccco, Firearms and Explosives bureau made an arbitrary assessment that rocket propellant was explosive, when this has no factual basis.  Ammonium Perchlorate (the primary component of propellant) does not explode - it burns.  If APCP exploded, no rocket would survive liftoff - including many NASA rockets which use this same propellant in their solid boosters.<br>
<br>
The 6000+ students in the nearly 500 High Schools nationwide participating in the Team America Rocketry Challenge will be denied their educational and inspirational experience should the current regulations be enforced.<br>
<br>
To address the concern regarding dangerous uses - those who are set upon destruction have far far better means at their disposal than using propellants that DO NOT EXPLODE.  The propane canister under your barbecue is more dangerous than a hobby rocket motor, but no one is asking you to be fingerprinted, background checked, and  have your home subject to unannounced inspection to purchase a propane tank.  Nor is anyone requiring you to store your propane tank in a 1/2 inch thick welded steel box with two heavy padlocks a hundred feet away from any building or road.<br>
<br>
But this is exactly what the ATFE is requiring of people who purchase hobby rocket motors that DO NOT EXPLODE.<br>
<br>
Fertilizer and fuel oil is used to manufacture illegal explosives with infinitely more destructive power than the largest hobby rocket motor, but no one is asking you to be subjected to the conditions I stated to purchase fertilizer for your garden, or fuel for your furnace or diesel.<br>
<br>
An owner of a &quot;antique firearm&quot; (e.g.; replica of a civil war rifle) can lawfully possess 50 lbs of Black Powder without a permit, but if a rocketeer puts 2 grams in a rocket to eject a parachute for recovery without a permit (and all the conditions stated) he is subject to a $10,000 fine and imprisionment.<br>
<br>
The regulation is unlawful, as ATFE does not have the authority to declare propellants explosive - hence the Tripoli/National Assoc of Rocketry lawsuit in progress.  The regulation also does nothing to address Homeland Security or public safety issues - hence Senator Enzi's proposed bill to exempt hobby rocketry materials from regulation.<br>
<br>
The regulation does put an opportunity for children and adults to learn practical aerospace principals, inspiring them in their careers, and to support of the national Space program.<br>
<br>
I appreciate concerns about security and safety, but extinguishing this wonderful hobby and shutting down dozens of small businesses which supply it is not a rational way to address those concerns.<br>
